title: How to make a short film with no money
contentMarkdown:
As a filmmaker I often get asked how I find producers for my short films. The simple answer is that I don’t. I have written and directed five short films so far, and four of them were no-budget. I have also helped make numerous other short films over the years for my collaborators at Studio Ronin, and most of those were made for no money. The market for short films is not lucrative, so for aspiring filmmakers, it’s better to spend time actually making films, instead of chasing after fictional producers.

But are these no budget films any good? It wouldn’t be fair of me to sing praises of my own work, all I can say is, my zero budget films have played alongside films with huge budgets and famous cast and crew, in festivals all over the world. My no budget sci-fi film Visionary was acquired and released by Pocket Films, played in 10 festivals, and was given a shoutout by critic Baradwaj Rangan on his blog. If nothing, making these films taught me the basics of filmmaking, filled my portfolio and helped me reach professionals for the films that did have a budget.

So how does one make a no-budget film? First, let’s take a reality check. Zero-budget does not actually mean zero cost. I own a camera. Granted, it’s five years old and costed lesser than a basic iPhone, but it does shoot 4K, and can change lenses. Film is a technical medium, and you need something to shoot with. If you don’t have a camera, you can borrow/rent one, or shoot on a phone. Also, there are always small miscellaneous expenses during shoots, especially on food and commutes. Always, always feed your crew well. Another cost that cannot be avoided is festival submission fees, but that comes later. 

Dream big but with your feet on the ground. If you’re planning to make the next big blockbuster superhero action film with world ending stakes on a zero budget, you are setting up yourself up to fail. Some stories need money, some stories don’t. Don’t try to make a story that needs money with an empty wallet. You cannot compete with the studios in terms of money and resources, but you can compete in terms of storytelling and creativity. For a no-budget filmmaker, it’s far more advisable to make simple and realistic grounded stories.

Reality check done, now let’s talk about how to actually make the film. Over the years, I have derived my process down to two primary rules. The first rule is – Use what you have. 

The usual process of making a film is that you write a script, and then gather the resources you need to make that script a reality, also known as pre-production. But on a zero-budget film, it’s better to take stock of your resources first, and reverse engineer a story based on what you have available to you. Think of the locations you have access to, it could be your house, a friend’s apartment, a classroom maybe, make a list of locations that you can shoot in without spending money. Think of things you have lying around in your house that can be used as props. Next, make a list of people who can act your in film, and come up with characters that are close to their personality. Most likely your actors will be your friends with little to no acting experience, so play to their strengths. Don’t make a 21 year college student play a middle-aged doctor. The more experienced your actor is, the more you can experiment. It’s better to rewrite a role to fit the actor, than to make the actor play a role they are not comfortable with.

But my friends don’t want to act, you say. Well neither did mine. You have to convince them, trade favours, beg if necessary. And it’s easier than it sounds. Everyone wants to be an actor. Once you have your actors, location and props, you need to come up with a story that uses only the elements you have, and nothing else. One might feel this is restrictive, but it’s actually the opposite. Constraints allow us to be more creative whereas abundance of resources can cripple our imagination. And within these constraints, you are free to go as high concept as you want. The starting point of my film Visionary, which is a mix of sci-fi and supernatural horror, was that I had access to an empty flat that I could shoot in. I wandered around the rooms of this flat, trying to visualise what kind of story could take place there, which is how I came up with idea of the film. Limitation fosters creativity.

It's best to write a script that can be filmed over the weekend, since everyone on the crew will be working on their off days. For a script in standard formatting, try to keep it under 10 pages, ie 10 minutes. You might feel it’s too short, but it’s long enough to have an impact. Write more than one story, discuss with your friends, bring them into the process. As for the actual shoot, finalise the shoot date before starting prep. All through this process, it’s important to remember the mantra that you must only use what you already have. Once you get into it, you’d be surprised at how many things you can get for free.

The second rule is – Do everything yourself (except acting)

The biggest cost in any film is people. So if you can’t afford to hire people, and if you don’t have filmmaker friends who will help you for free, you have to do it yourself. And it can be done, there are enough resources on the internet to teach yourself the basics of any skill, it just takes a lot of time and effort. Yes, you won’t be as good as a professional, but you can get pretty damn close. And it’s also the best way to learn. On most of my films, I have written, directed, produced, edited, and everything in between. If I had waited for a ‘team’ to materialise and make my film for me, I would still be waiting. Once you have a few films behind you, it’s easier to find collaborators. Till then, you have to tough it out. I suggest not going solo, because cinema at its heart is a collaborative medium, and actors can double as crew. 

There is another rule above all, that is to have fun. But that happens automatically. Just go for it. Don’t let the fear of failure hold you back. The worst that can happen is that you make a bad film. But even a bad film is better than no film at all.
